nodes.bodyText:
@gregw having multiple subscriptions for the same content is not a use case that we need implemented. If someone wants to do that, the API does not forbid it, but we don't need it.
It will be quite complicated to implement multiple subscriptions, as one will be slower than the other, and now you need a policy to decide whether the chunks should be provided independently, or wait for all the subscribers to demand, etc.
The fact that the subscription is overwritten in case of reproducible content is because the same content may be reproduced in a subsequent request (e.g. 302 or 401), so the subscriptions are sequential (not simultaneous), but only ever one is active.

